in the long lines and spaces of the staff. Ladies' voices are higher than men's voices,
and in order to represent the pitches these two classes of voices sing, the staff is
made to represent pitches in two ways. When it is wanted to represent the pitch-
es that ladies sing, this character,
called the TREBLE CLEF, is put upon it.

9: called the BASE CLEF, is put upon it. The staff then represents pitches

81. The first added line below when the treble clef is used, and the first added
above when the base clef is used, represent the same pitch C, and are the centre
and junctional point of the two staves. The pitch they jointly represent is about
midway the male and female voices, and is called MIDDLE C. See the following
82. Every scale and tune is within some key. One of every scale is called the
key-tone, and the pitch taken for the key-tone gives name to the key. Thus, if C
be one, the scale or tune is in the key of C; if D be one, it is in the key of D; etc.
83. Musical instruction usually begins with the key of C. The staff is made to
represent the key of C by having none of its degrees modified; thus,
Do, Re, Mi, Fa, Sol, La, Si, Do.
